Babylonios, more generally called Chaldaeos. The ancient Chal- daeans were the first astronomers and we inherit from them the division of the circle into 360 degrees and of the hour into 60 minutes. In later times they were noted chiefly as astrologers, who pretended to under- stand the influence of the stars on human destiny. They had a large following in Rome and under the empire frequent attempts were made to put them down. Horace himself was not free from the superstition which he here decries. In 11. 17. 21 he tells Maecenas utrumque nostrum incredibili modo consentit astrum.
